huh?  Then where did the plat go?  Here's a little example.  If he scams someone for 20k, spends it all on gear, and soon after decides that he made a big mistake and needs to fix it, as he claims to have done, then the solution is very simple.  He just bought 20k in gear.  Time to sell that gear.  How the heck does that leave him with nothing?  He'd have whatever he had before he did the scam minus perhaps a small depreciation in item value.  It was a short period of time between the scam and the beg for forgiveness, so there wouldn't be much change in item value anyway.  I asked this question earlier and go no satisfactory response, just more people saying &quot;give him a chance! give him a chance!&quot;.  Oh, and how could we forget his post saying that he had to keep a few k back to buy a new helm?  Give me a break.  Unless he scammed the plat and then gave it away to charity (yeah right, lol) then he should have plat plus gear bought with the scam money that is worth almost as much as the original amount scammed and reimbursing people should only take as long as it takes to sell whatever he bought with his ill gotten gains.  That's it.  The long delays are unacceptable if he truly expects forgiveness.  It looks like he's turned his scam money into a long term loan that he'll profit from and eventually pay back when it is convenient in hopes of being totally forgiven. <br>
<br>
Okay, theoretically he could end up with less stuff than he had before the scams if he stupidly bought gear at inflated prices with his scam money.  That would be his own dumb fault and he'd deserve to pay the price for it.<br>
<br>
of course if he really does quit the server, the money will never be paid back and attempts to clear his name are a mute point.<br>
